column8: SQL defines two primary character types: character varying(n) and character(n)\
column9: where n is a positive integer. Both of these types can store strings up to n characters (not bytes) in length. An attempt to store a longer string into a column of these types will result in an error\
column10: unless the excess characters are all spaces\
column11: in which case the string will be truncated to the maximum length. (This somewhat bizarre exception is required by the SQL standard.) If the string to be stored is shorter than the declared length\
column12: values of type character will be space-padded; values of type character varying will simply store the shorter string.
